<author><name><![CDATA[blargg]]></name></author>
<updated>2008-12-08T17:07:22-07:00</updated>
<published>2008-12-08T17:07:22-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4640&amp;p=40607#p40607</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4640&amp;p=40607#p40607"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[New minimal blip library for sound chip emulation]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=4640&amp;p=40607#p40607"><![CDATA[
I've finished a minimal band-limited synthesis library for use in sound chip emulation:<br /><br /><a href="http://h1.ripway.com/blargg/temp/blip-1.0.0.zip" class="postlink">blip-1.0.0.zip</a><br /><br />It's in C and much simpler than my older Blip_Buffer library. It includes documentation and some demos, including one that emulates NES-like sound hardware and plays back a log of sound writes to it. I think it really simplifies writing a sound chip emulator, allowing focus on the essential aspects, without getting bogged down in resampling output for the PC's lower sample rate.<br /><br />I'm most interested in feedback on how easy it is to use. Thanks.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17">blargg</a> — Mon Dec 08, 2008 5:07 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
